<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I259d25a0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>C.</label.designator><headtext>Examination</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05da682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:17.</label.designator><headtext>Examining witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In Georgia, a witness may not testify to a matter unless evidence supports a finding that the witness has personal knowledge of the matter, and he will be presumed to be doing so if <page no="20"/>nothing to the contrary appears.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1af49007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] A witness must have observed a sensory fact and cannot state conclusions or beliefs not based on his firsthand knowledge.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Normally, one counsel for each party may question a witness. <eos/><bos/>Additionally, the court has a right, even a duty, to question witnesses,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1af70107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] but must not ask questions that discredit the witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1af70117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] It is difficult for the court to conduct extensive questioning of a witness without becoming an advocate.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1af97207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] It is reversible error for the court to express or intimate its opinion regarding what has or has not been proven or the guilt of the accused.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1af97217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] Interestingly, the court in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1970134833" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55638227fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>King v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1af97227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] asked two questions of the defendant and 41 questions of a defense witness during cross-examination without expressing an opinion.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A court&apos;s remarks to counsel regarding conduct of his cross-examination, discussing the admissibility of evidence, or explaining its rulings do not constitute expressions of opinion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1afbe307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] In addition, a court&apos;s comments to a pro se party regarding the appropriateness and relevance of his comments do not constitute an expression of opinion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1afbe317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court must be careful to avoid the appearance of an expression of opinion while speaking to counsel or giving jury instructions. <eos/><bos/>For example, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018405690" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id5580ce27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Gardner v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1afe5407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] the appellate court ordered a new trial because the trial court asked the prosecution whether “we” had proven venue yet. <eos/><bos/>The appellate court felt that the judge&apos;s use of this word might have caused the jury to believe that the trial judge and prosecutor were aligned. <eos/><bos/>Whether the trial judge intended to express an opinion was irrelevant.<eos/><page no="21"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2017943852" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id5596c727fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hargett v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1afe5417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] the trial court did not express an opinion on the facts by giving the standard pattern jury instruction regarding prior consistent statements. <eos/><bos/>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018423716" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55a56d27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Rolland v. State</ital></cite.query>, the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a jury could have reasonably taken the court&apos;s instruction, which substantially tracked the language of the child hearsay statute, to be an expression of opinion that a minor child&apos;s statements were reliable or true.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1b00c507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>] Jurors may question a witness only by submitting a question to the court.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1b00c517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The calling and interrogation of witnesses by the court is governed by <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-614" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id55ceee07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-614</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1b033607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13</footnote.reference>] which provides that the court may call parties to the stand, either on its own motion or at the suggestion of a party. <eos/><bos/>If the court calls a witness, all parties are then entitled to cross-examine the witness. <eos/><bos/>The court also has the right to interrogate any witness called by itself or by a party. <eos/><bos/>Parties have the right to object to the court calling a witness or interrogating a witness called by a party. <eos/><bos/>Such objections may be made at the time or at the next available time when the jury is not present.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1b033617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2036747589" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Id55e75817fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>U.S. v. Khan,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic1b05a707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">15</footnote.reference>] the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that it was within the court&apos;s discretion to allow a government translator to insert bracketed words into a translation. <eos/><bos/>In that case, the trial court instructed the government to place the translator on the stand to describe the process of his translation and the reasoning for his bracketed insertions, and directed opposing counsel to cross-examine the translator, or provide another translator to rebut the testimony, thus making translators subject to the rules of evidence.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic1af49007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-602" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id552dcc07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-602</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>This is consistent with <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER602" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Id552dcc17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 602</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1958122454" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id552dcc47fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Canal Ins. Co. v. Winge Bros., Inc., 97 Ga. App. 782, 104 S.E.2d 525 (1958)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1981124747" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id552dcc77fbf11ea988285db8533e975">McCann v. State, 158 Ga. App. 202, 279 S.E.2d 499 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1af70107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1978196209" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id553a0127fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thomas v. State, 240 Ga. 393, 242 S.E.2d 1 (1977)</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="0280312268" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="Id553a0137fbf11ea988285db8533e975">McCormick on Evidence § 8 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1af70117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1977114722" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55463627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Griffin v. State, 142 Ga. App. 362, 235 S.E.2d 724 (1977)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment vacated on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1978109896" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55463657fbf11ea988285db8533e975">240 Ga. 470, 241 S.E.2d 230 (1978)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1977135061" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55463687fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brundage v. State, 143 Ga. App. 1, 237 S.E.2d 473 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1af97207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1907012282" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Id554ffa27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ford v. State, 2 Ga. App. 834, 59 S.E. 88 (1907)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1979129024" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id554ffa57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Stinson v. State, 151 Ga. App. 533, 260 S.E.2d 407 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1af97217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-10-7" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id55574d07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 9-10-7</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-8-57" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id55574d17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">17-8-57</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1965126860" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55574d47fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Atlanta Stove Works, Inc. v. Hollon, 112 Ga. App. 862, 146 S.E.2d 358 (1965)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1986138259" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55574d77fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Cannon v. State, 179 Ga. App. 142, 345 S.E.2d 623 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1af97227fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1970134833" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55686427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">King v. State, 121 Ga. App. 347, 173 S.E.2d 746 (1970)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1afbe307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018849318" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id556fb727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Green v. State, 298 Ga. App. 17, 679 S.E.2d 348 (2009)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1afbe317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018626397" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55770a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Muskett v. Sketchley Cleaners, Inc., 297 Ga. App. 561, 677 S.E.2d 731 (2009)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1afe5407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018405690" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id5585b027fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Gardner v. State, 296 Ga. App. 792, 794–95, 676 S.E.2d 258 (2009)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2021254222" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id5585b057fbf11ea988285db8533e975">286 Ga. 633, 690 S.E.2d 164 (2010)</cite.query> and <case.history>opinion vacated in part</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2022674199" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id5585b087fbf11ea988285db8533e975">305 Ga. App. 492, 700 S.E.2d 214 (2010)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="21"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1afe5417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2017943852" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55993827fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Hargett v. State, 285 Ga. 82, 674 S.E.2d 261 (2009)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1b00c507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2018423716" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55aa4f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Rolland v. State, 296 Ga. App. 889, 676 S.E.2d 296 (2009)</cite.query> (trial court&apos;s finding that the circumstances of a child&apos;s statement provided “sufficient indicia of reliability” as required by the child hearsay statute was reversible error).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1973127017" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55b41327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Central of Georgia Ry. Co. v. Luther, 128 Ga. App. 178, 182, 196 S.E.2d 149 (1973)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1981108820" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55b41357fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. State, 247 Ga. 268, 275 S.E.2d 67 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, if the witness has presented the data to the jury in such a way that the jury could draw the inference as well as the witness, then it is improper to let the witness state an opinion. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1979128216" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55bdd727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Calloway v. Rossman, 150 Ga. App. 381, 257 S.E.2d 913 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A witness must testify from his own firsthand knowledge. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1984114456" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55c52a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Garrett v. State, 169 Ga. App. 327, 312 S.E.2d 621 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1b00c517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="1981116955" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id55ca0c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Story v. State, 157 Ga. App. 490, 278 S.E.2d 97 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1b033607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER614" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Id55d3d007fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 614</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1b033617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-614" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id55db2307fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-614</cite.query>; Weinstein&apos;s Evidence, page 614 (01)–(04).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic1b05a707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018090" w-serial-number="2036747589" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Id55f38d17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. Khan, 794 F.3d 1288 (11th Cir. 2015)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="22"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
